The Primate Inner Ear Canal System

Dan Wawrzyniak

December 5, 2016

Question

Do the size of the semicircular canals of the inner ear of primates correlate to postural and/or locomotor behaviour?

  • Why do I care?
  • Subarcuate fossa volume is positively correlated with increased body mass and increased canal volume (Jeffery et al. 2008)
  • Humans and other great apes are weird: Have large canals but lack a true subarcuate fossa
  • Hylobatids possess a true subarcuate fossa, but it is smaller than expected in relation to body size and canal size (Jeffery et al. 2008)
  • Along with Hylobatids, spider monkeys (Ateles geoffroyi) are outliers
  • Across mammals, size of the canals is positively correlated with faster, jerkier, more agile locomotion (Spoor et al. 2007)
  • ….So, among primates (catarrhines), are the size of the semicircular canals correlated to postural and locomotor behaviours they employ?

Jeffery et al. 2008

Hunt 2016

Data

  • Spoor et al. 2007 data on body mass and semicircular canals (using mean radius)

  • Hunt 2016 data on primate behaviour

  • Result: 24 species of Catarrhines

  • Phylogenetic tree from 10k Trees (Consensus tree of 10,000 trees generated by Bayesian inference)

Manipulating Data

  • Combine
  • Change seperator
  • Change species names which don’t match in phylogeny
  • Reorder data species according to phylogeny order
  • comparative.data() to combine tree with data
Canals <- Canals[,c(1,2,8,13)]

All_data <- left_join(Behaviour, Canals, by = "Species")

All_data$Species <- gsub(" ", "_", All_data$Species)

Tree$tip.label <- gsub("Cercocebus_torquatus_atys", "Cercocebus_atys", Tree$tip.label)

Tree$tip.label <- gsub("Bunopithecus_hoolock", "Hoolock_hoolock", Tree$tip.label)

Tree$tip.label <- gsub("Pan_troglodytes_troglodytes", "Pan_troglodytes", Tree$tip.label)

Tree$tip.label <- gsub("Chlorocebus_aethiops", "Cercopithecus_aethiops", Tree$tip.label)

All_data$Species <- reorder.factor(All_data$Species, new.order = Tree$tip.label)

All_data <- All_data %>% arrange(Species)

forPGLS <- comparative.data(phy = Tree, data = All_data, names.col = "Species")

The first loop

for(i in 2:19) {

    A <- lm( logSCR ~ logBM + All_data[ ,i], data = All_data )

}

Multiple Regression

Preparing for Second Loop

mycomb <- function(x) {
  sort(x) %>% paste(collapse = "-")
}

Check <- character()
Dupli <- logical()

Addresses the following issues:

  • Duplicated runs (e.g. Quad.Stand-Suspensory, Suspensory-Quad.Stand)
  • Errors in computing model because of many low/zero values

Both of the above speed up the loop run by eliminating unnecessary runs before they happen

Multiple Regression

The Second Loop

for(i in 2:19) {
  for(j in 2:19) {
    if(i != j) {
    Check[length(Check) + 1] <- mycomb(c(names(All_data[i]), names(All_data[j])))
    Dupli <- duplicated(Check)
    if(Dupli[length(Dupli)] == FALSE) {
      A <- lm( logSCR ~ logBM + All_data[ ,i] + All_data[ ,j], data = All_data )
      
      Multreg[length(Multreg$Dependent_Variable) + 1, ] <- c("logSCR", "logBM", 
                                             names(All_data[i]),
                                             names(All_data[j]), "NA", "NA", 
                                             summary(A)$adj.r.squared,
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[2,4], 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[3,4], 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[4,4],"NA", 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[1,1], 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[2,1], 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[3,1], 
                                             summary(A)$coefficients[4,1], "NA")
      
    }
  }
  }
}

Multiple Regression

…and Finally…

Check <- character()
Dupli <- logical()

for(i in 2:19) {
  for(j in 2:19) {
    if(i != j) {
      for(k in 2:19) {
        if(j != k) {
          if(i != k) {
            
    Check[length(Check) + 1] <- mycomb(c(names(All_data[i]), names(All_data[j]), 
                                        names(All_data[k])))
    Dupli <- duplicated(Check)
    if(Dupli[length(Dupli)] == FALSE) {
    Try <- try(lm( logSCR ~ logBM + All_data[ ,i] + All_data[ ,j] + 
                              All_data[ ,k], data = All_data ), silent = TRUE)
    if(class(Try) == "try-error") {
    }else{
    A <- lm( logSCR ~ logBM + All_data[ ,i] + All_data[ ,j] + All_data[ ,k], 
                                                            data = All_data)
    if(length(anova(A)$Df) == 5) {  
      Multreg[length(Multreg$Dependent_Variable) + 1, ] <- c("logSCR", "logBM", 
              names(All_data[i]), names(All_data[j]), names(All_data[k]), "NA", 
                        summary(A)$adj.r.squared, summary(A)$coefficients[2,4], 
                    summary(A)$coefficients[3,4], summary(A)$coefficients[4,4], 
                    summary(A)$coefficients[5,4], summary(A)$coefficients[1,1], 
                    summary(A)$coefficients[2,1], summary(A)$coefficients[3,1], 
                    summary(A)$coefficients[4,1], summary(A)$coefficients[5,1])
              } } } } } } } } }

PGLS Regression for selected OLS models

for(i in 1:10){
  l <- Multreg[i,3]
  m <- Multreg[i,4]
  n <- Multreg[i,5]
  if(Multreg[i,5] == "NA") {
    A <- pgls( logSCR ~ logBM + forPGLS$data[[l]] + forPGLS$data[[m]], data = forPGLS, lambda = "ML")
    Multreg[length(Multreg$Dependent_Variable) + 1, ] <- c("logSCR", "logBM", names(forPGLS$data[l]),
    names(forPGLS$data[m]), "NA", as.numeric(summary(A)$param.CI$lambda$opt), 
    summary(A)$adj.r.squared, summary(A)$coefficients[2,4], summary(A)$coefficients[3,4], 
    summary(A)$coefficients[4,4],"NA", summary(A)$coefficients[1,1], 
    summary(A)$coefficients[2,1], summary(A)$coefficients[3,1], summary(A)$coefficients[4,1], "NA")
    } else {
    A <- pgls( logSCR ~ logBM + forPGLS$data[[l]] + forPGLS$data[[m]] + forPGLS$data[[n]] , data = forPGLS, lambda = "ML")
    Multreg[length(Multreg$Dependent_Variable) + 1, ] <- c("logSCR", "logBM", names(forPGLS$data[l]),
    names(forPGLS$data[m]), names(forPGLS$data[n]), as.numeric(summary(A)$param.CI$lambda$opt), 
    summary(A)$adj.r.squared, summary(A)$coefficients[2,4], summary(A)$coefficients[3,4], 
    summary(A)$coefficients[4,4], summary(A)$coefficients[5,4], summary(A)$coefficients[1,1], 
    summary(A)$coefficients[2,1], summary(A)$coefficients[3,1], summary(A)$coefficients[4,1], 
    summary(A)$coefficients[5,1])
    }
}

Reorder and interpret results

Interpreting Results

  • p- values for best models are significant
  • But…r- squared < .6
  • For some lambda = ~0, others near .5
  • Most best fit models are 3 predictors, with the exception of Quad.Stand + Suspensory
  • All data only availible for Catarrhines
  • Small sample size (24 species;n=1 of each species included)
